Sure, here's an example of an API datasource file as used in Godspeed's microservice framework:

```
import { ApiDataSource } from '@godspeedjs/api';

class MyApiDataSource extends ApiDataSource {
  constructor(apiKey: string) {
    super({
      baseURL: 'https://api.example.com',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'X-Api-Key': apiKey,
      },
    });
  }

  async getMyData() {
    const { data } = await this.get('/my-data');
    return data;
  }

  async postMyData(payload) {
    const { data } = await this.post('/my-data', payload);
    return data;
  }
}

export default MyApiDataSource;
```

In this example, the `MyApiDataSource` class extends the `ApiDataSource` class provided by Godspeed's `@godspeedjs/api` package. The `MyApiDataSource` constructor takes an API key as a parameter, which is used to set the `X-Api-Key` header on all requests.

The class also defines two methods, `getMyData` and `postMyData`, which make GET and POST requests, respectively, to the `/my-data` endpoint on the remote API. These methods use the `get` and `post` methods provided by the `ApiDataSource` class to make the requests, and return the `data` property of the response.

To use this API datasource in a Godspeed microservice, you would import it into your service file and instantiate it with the appropriate API key, like this:

```
import MyApiDataSource from './MyApiDataSource';

const myApiKey = '12345';

const myApi = new MyApiDataSource(myApiKey);

export default myApi;
```

In a Godspeed project, you can define an API data source by creating a file in the `src/datasources` directory with a name that ends with `.api.ts`. For example, `myapi.api.ts`. In this file, you can define the endpoints of the API using the `@endpoint` decorator provided by Godspeed.

Here's an example of how you can define an API data source for a simple REST API:

```typescript
import { endpoint } from "@godspeedjs/godspeed";

@endpoint({
  baseUrl: "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com",
})
export class MyApi {
  @endpoint({ method: "GET", path: "/posts" })
  getPosts() {}

  @endpoint({ method: "GET", path: "/posts/{id}" })
  getPostById(id: number) {}

  @endpoint({ method: "POST", path: "/posts" })
  createPost(data: { title: string; body: string; userId: number }) {}

  @endpoint({ method: "PUT", path: "/posts/{id}" })
  updatePostById(id: number, data: { title: string; body: string }) {}

  @endpoint({ method: "DELETE", path: "/posts/{id}" })
  deletePostById(id: number) {}
}
```

In this example, we've defined an API data source called `MyApi` with the base URL of `"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com"`. We've also defined five endpoints for this API, using the `@endpoint` decorator.

Each endpoint is defined with an HTTP method and a path. For example, the `getPosts()` endpoint is a `GET` request to the `/posts` path. The `getPostById(id: number)` endpoint is a `GET` request to the `/posts/{id}` path, where `{id}` is a parameter.

You can define more complex endpoints that include query parameters, headers, and request bodies. You can also define middleware functions to intercept and modify requests and responses before they are sent or received by the endpoint.
